shared_text:
Woodland Park School District added 19 new photos.
June 19 at 9:28 AM ·

The Class of 2020 graduated from Memorial Middle School on June 18 in a unique drive-by event held at Passaic Valley H.S. It was a historic event for both Memorial School and Borough of Woodland Park. In 1958, the first 8th grade graduation was held in the gymnasium. Each year students graduated in the gym until the event was moved to Passaic Valley H.S. Last night the Class of 2020 made history by being the first WP class to graduate outside at PVHS. #ProudtobeWP

Band and chorus students sent video and audio recordings of themselves to music director Eric Schaefer. He has taken the hundreds of files they've sent and put them together for the concert. The theme is "Together through Music,” with the goal of bringing the Woodland Park/Memorial community together. Mr. Schaefer’s hope is that the concert gives a sense of normalcy and familiarity in the unsettling times we're living through. The video will be live at 7 p.m. at https://youtu.be/hZ1bVNG0aTQ. #ProudtobeWP

post_text:
The Wellness Week Challenge, sponsored by our school nurses, kicks off today. Each day, take a photo and send it to your school nurse. Each photo is an entry to a random lottery where one student from each grade will win a prize.
* Mask on Monday, 6/1 - Show us you are wearing your mask
* Twinning Tuesday, 6/2 - Take a twinning picture to show you know how to social distance, but can still have fun being safe
* Wash Your Hands Wednesday, 6/3 - Show us that you are practicing good hand hygiene
* Thoughtfulness Thursday, 6/4 - What have you done to help someone during this time”
* Free Friday, 6/5 - Pick your favorite physical activity and take a picture doing it.

post_text: Parents are invited to view a few webinar tonight at 6:30 p.m. - "ABCs of Quarantine: A virtual program for K-5 parents & caregivers." Many parents are struggling to maintain attention, balance, and connection in this new home-school-work environment. You are not alone. Clinician Linda Price will provide strategies for managing family life, including: mindful parenting, reducing stress, creating balance, enhancing your child’s social connections. post_text:
An update from Mayor Kazmark:

I regret to inform you that that we have been informed by County Health Officials of the first presumptive positive COVID-19 test of a Woodland Park resident.
The resident is a 21-year-old male. He is quarantined at home and is currently asymptomatic.
We remain in constant contact with the Director of County Health and will release additional information as it is provided. I want to stress this is not a time for panic or overzealous concern.
While this resident is presumptive positive, there remains little immediate risk of exposure to this virus. However, we must be vigilant in following the recommendations of Public Health Officials when it comes to social distancing, hand washing, covering coughs and sneezes and disinfecting common areas.
Should you exhibit any symptoms of illness, consult your personal doctor to discuss treatment.
Please be patient as we continue to work to provide accurate information to the public. Stay well.

post_text:
After much collaboration and communication with district leaders throughout and around our region and county, the decision has been made to activate our Alternative Learning Plan and close our school buildings. During this time, students are expected to follow the Alternative Learning Plan, which has been sent home with them today.

Woodland Park Public Schools will be closed from Monday, March 16 to Friday, March 27, at which point the situation will be reassessed.

While there are NO confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Woodland Park at this time, this action is being taken in an effort to slow the rapidly spreading Coronavirus.

All school activities are canceled/postponed effective Saturday, March 14 until further notice. This includes before-care and after-care, evening events and activities. Note that the Board of Education meeting scheduled for Monday, March 23 at 7 p.m. will still be conducted.

post_text:
School officials have reviewed procedures and have put in contingency plans in place relative to coronavirus.
The custodial staff at each of our schools have increased daily disinfection efforts and there will be a deep cleaning of facilities each weekend for the next four weeks.
Parents and students are urged to take necessary precautions: frequent hand washing, staying home if sick, and limiting hand to hand contact.
There are no plans for the school district to close for planning purposes at this time. Our staff members are utilizing prep time to plan for any type of long term closure, should it become necessary. If a closure becomes necessary, we would institute a combination of online teaching via Google Classroom, as well as textbook/paper based for those without computer access.
Officials are in constant contact with the county Health Department, the Borough and Office of Emergency Management. Updates will be posted as they become available.

post_text: Beatrice Gilmore kicked off the “One School, One Book” program at an assembly where their mascot Buddy The Bear appeared, wearing an inflatable ball as a clue - a hamster wheel. He unwrapped the book revealing the title -“Friendship According to Humphrey.” The WP Municipal Alliance purchased copies for every student and staff member. Everyone is reading the book together, a chapter a night, and the book is theirs to keep. #ProudtobeWP

post_text:
The Woodland Park School District announces the recipients of the annual New Jersey Governor's Teacher/Educational Services Professional of the Year for 2019-2020. These awards are voted on from nominations from parents and students.
The winners are as follows:
Charles Olbon – kindergarten teacher Mrs. Tundo and speech therapist Mrs. Farsakh
Beatrice Gilmore – fourth grade teacher Ms. D'Astolfo and library aide Mrs. De Rosa
Memorial – physical education and health teacher Robert Romeo and classroom aide Dalia Alhatto
#ProudtobeWP

post_text: A postcard exchange project in 4-Wilson/D'Astolfo's class at Beatrice Gilmore School in Woodland Park is in full swing. Students researched facts and fun information about New Jersey from a variety of sources. Students then worked on letter writing skills and together composed a postcard to be sent out to the other 49 states. The class is enjoying the postcards that are coming in from other states. Students are learning information from peers across the country, and comparing and contrasting geography and culture of each with our own. #ProudtobeWP
